2026-04-21 01:30:08 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['PSU output cabling / polarity configuration at source', 'Load-module protection diode'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show the PSU “+” output is at −12 V relative to ground and the “−” at 0 V, while the green supply LED (wired to light only for +12 V on its designated terminal) is off. The control-module inversion LED is on, confirming reversed polarity between its internal reference and the incoming lines. Thus, the external 12 V source (battery/wall wart) is connected with reversed polarity relative to the PSU module’s internal labeling, or the PSU output leads are swapped internally, giving an effective polarity inversion at the series chain.\n\nAt the load module, with the control module passing this reversed potential, the supposed protection diode is measured with its anode at −11.99 V and its cathode and both lamp terminals at about 0 V. This indicates the diode is conducting heavily (approximately the full supply across it) but dropping almost the entire voltage, leaving essentially 0 V across the lamp. That behaviour is consistent with the diode either being installed backwards (schematic vs. real wiring) or internally shorted/open in such a way that it clamps the supply instead of passing it to the lamp. The low resistance (~1.7 Ω) path from the return cable to the diode node supports the presence of a low-impedance path around the lamp due to the mis‑oriented or failed diode.\n\nCombined, these faults explain all symptoms: reversed PSU polarity turns off the green LED and turns on the control-module red inversion indicator, while the miswired/faulty load protection diode prevents any voltage from appearing across the lamp, so it never lights even when the switch is operated. Reconnecting the 12 V source with correct polarity relative to the PSU module terminals (or correcting the PSU output lead assignment) and replacing/reorienting the load-module protection diode should restore normal operation.'
